First toggle exercise: get it working.<br>
<div data-controller="toggle"
  data-toggle-primary-class="text-primary">
  <div data-toggle-target="button" class="hideable">Peekaboo</div>
  <button class="btn" data-action="toggle#clicked">
    Toggle
  </button>
</div>

<br>

Second toggle exercise: show a dropdown menu. <br>
<div data-controller="toggle"
  data-toggle-primary-class="text-primary">
  <div data-toggle-target="button" class="hideable">
    <a href="#">Link 1</a><br>
    <a href="#">Link 2</a><br>
    <a href="#">Link 3</a><br>
  </div>
  <button class="btn" data-action="toggle#clicked">
    Toggle
  </button>
</div>

<br>

Third toggle exercise: hide the clicked element and show another. <br>
<div data-controller="toggle"
  data-toggle-primary-class="text-primary">
  <div data-toggle-target="button" class="hideable">
    <a href="#">Link 1</a><br>
    <a href="#">Link 2</a><br>
    <a href="#">Link 3</a><br>
  </div>
  <button class="hideable" data-toggle-target="button2" data-action="toggle#clicked">
    Toggle
  </button>
</div>

<br>

Fourth toggle exercise: Clicking a checkbox will highlight the element containing the checkbox. <br>
<div data-controller="toggle"
  data-toggle-primary-class="text-primary">
  <div class="highlight" data-toggle-target="button2">
  <input type="checkbox" data-action="toggle#clicked">
    Toggle
  </button>
  </div>
</div>

<br>

Fifth toggle exercise: Write a controller for text inputs with a limited length. Warn a user when they are close or over the maximum character count (imagine a user writing a post which has a maximum length of 280 characters)

<div data-controller="text-counter" data-text-counter-max-value="280">
  <textarea data-text-counter-target="input" data-action="text-counter#input"></textarea>
  <div data-text-counter-target="output"></div>
</div>